	X.ng comp.unix ,
	Xbut
	X.cn B
	Xdoes not receive
	X.ng btl.general .
	X.cn A
	Xmust leave the
	X.hf Newsgroups
	Xline unchanged.
	XIf it were to remove
	X.ng btl.general ,
	Xthe edited header could eventually reenter the
	X.ng btl.all
	Xclass,
	Xresulting in an article that is not shown to users subscribing to
	X.ng btl.general .
	XAlso,
	Xfollowups from outside
	X.ng btl.all
	Xwould not be shown to such users.
	X.hn 3
	XSubject
	X.pg
	XThe
	X.hf Subject
	Xline
	X(formerly
	X.hf Title )
	Xtells what the article is about.
	XIt should be suggestive enough of the contents of the article
	Xto enable a reader to make a decision whether to read the article
	Xbased on the subject alone.
	XIf the article is submitted in response to another article
	X.i e\f1.\fPg ., (
	Xis a
	X.i followup )
	Xthe default subject should begin with the four characters \*(lqRe: \*(rq
	Xand the
	X.hf Reference
	Xline is required.
	X(The user might wish to edit the subject of the followup,
	Xbut the default should begin with \*(lqRe: \*(rq.)
	X.hn 3
	XMessage-ID
	X.pg
	XThe
	X.hf Message-ID
	Xline gives the article a unique identifier.
	XThe same Message-ID may not be reused during the lifetime of any article
	Xwith the same Message-ID.
	X(It is recommended that no Message-ID be reused for at least two years.)
	XMessage-ID's have the syntax
	X.sd c
	X<\f2string not containing blank or \*(lq>\*(rq\fP>
	X.ed
	XIn order to conform to RFC 822,
	Xthe Message-ID must have the format
	X.sd c
	X<\f2unique\fP@\f2full_domain_name\fP>
	X.ed
	Xwhere
	X.i "full_domain_name"
	Xis the full name of the host at which the article entered the network,
	Xincluding a domain that host is in,
	Xand
	X.i unique
	Xis any string of printing ASCII characters,
	Xnot including
	X\*(lq<\*(rq (left angle bracket),
	X\*(lq>\*(rq (right angle bracket),
	Xor \*(lq@\*(rq (at sign).
	XFor example,
	Xthe
	X.i unique
	Xpart could be an integer representing a sequence number
	Xfor articles submitted to the network,
	Xor a short string derived from the date and time the article was created.
	XFor example,
	Xa valid Message-ID for an article submitted from site
	X.cn ucbvax
	Xin domain
	X.cf Berkeley.EDU
	Xwould be
	X.cf <4123@ucbvax.Berkeley.EDU> .
	XProgrammers are urged not to make assumptions
	Xabout the content of Message-ID fields from other hosts,
	Xbut to treat them as unknown character strings.
	XIt is not safe,
	Xfor example,
	Xto assume that a Message-ID will be under 14 characters,
	Xthat it is unique in the first 14 characters, nor that
	Xis does not contain a \*(lq/\*(rq.
	X.pg
	XThe angle brackets are considered part of the Message-ID.
	XThus,
	Xin references to the Message-ID,
	Xsuch as the
	X.pa ihave/sendme
	Xand
	X.b cancel
	Xcontrol messages,
	Xthe angle brackets are included.
	XWhite space characters
	X.i e\f1.\fPg ., (
	Xblank and tab)
	Xare not allowed in a Message-ID.
	XSlashes (\*(lq/\*(rq) are strongly discouraged.
	XAll characters between the angle brackets must be printing ASCII characters.
	X.hn 3
	XPath
	X.pg
	XThis line shows the path the article took to reach the current system.
	XWhen a system forwards the message,
	Xit should add its own name to the list of systems in the
	X.hf Path
	Xline.
	XThe names may be separated by any punctuation character or characters
	X(except \*(lq.\*(rq which is considered part of the hostname).
	XThus
	X.cf cbosgd!mhuxj!mhuxt ,
	X.cf "cbosgd, mhuxj, mhuxt" ,
	X.cf "@cbosgd.uucp,@mhuxj.uucp,@mhuxt.uucp"
	Xand even
	X.cf "teklabs, zehntel, sri-unix@cca!decvax"
	Xare valid entries.
	X(The latter path indicates a message that passed through
	X.cn decvax ,
	X.cn cca ,
	X.cn sri-unix ,
	X.cn zehntel ,
	Xand
	X.cn teklabs ,
	Xin that order.)
	XAdditional names should be added from the left,
	Xfor example,
	Xthe most recently added name in the third example was
	X.cn teklabs .
	XLetters,
	Xdigits,
	Xperiods and hyphens are considered part of site names;
	Xother punctuation,
	Xincluding blanks,
	Xare considered separators.
	X.pg
	XNormally,
	Xthe rightmost name will be the name of the originating system.
	XHowever,
	Xit is also permissible to include an extra entry on the right,
	Xwhich is the name of the sender.
	XThis is for upward compatibility with older system.
	X.pg
	XThe
	X.hf Path
	Xline is not used for replies,
	Xand should not be taken as a mailing address.
	XIt is intended to show the route
	Xthe message traveled to reach the local site.
	XThere are several uses for this information.
	XOne is to monitor USENET routing for performance reasons.
	XAnother is to establish a path to reach new sites.
	XPerhaps the most important is to cut down on redundant USENET traffic
	Xby failing to forward a message to a site that is
	Xknown to have already received it.
	XIn particular,
	Xwhen site
	X.cn A
	Xsends an article to site
	X.cn B ,
	Xthe
	X.hf Path
	Xline includes
	X.cn A ,
	Xso that site
	X.cn B
	Xwill not immediately send the article back to site
	X.cn A .
	XThe site name each site uses to identify itself should be
	Xthe same as the name by which its neighbors know it,
	Xin order to make this optimization possible.
	X.pg
	XA site adds its own name to the front of a path
	Xwhen it receives a message from another site.
	XThus, if a message with path
	X.cf A!X!Y!Z
	Xis passed from site
	X.cn A
	Xto site
	X.cn B ,
	X.cn B
	Xwill add its own name to the path when it receives the message from
	X.cn A ,
	X.i e\f1.\fPg .,
	X.cf \*(lqB!A!X!Y!Z\*(rq .
	XIf
	X.cn B
	Xthen passes the message on to
	X.cn C ,
	Xthe message sent to
	X.cn C
	Xwill contain the path
	X.cf B!A!X!Y!Z ,
	Xand when
	X.cn C
	Xreceives it,
	X.cn C
	Xwill change it to
	X.cf C!B!A!X!Y!Z .
	X.pg
	XSpecial upward compatibility note:
	XSince the
	X.hf From ,
	X.hf Sender ,
	Xand
	X.hf Reply-To
	Xlines are in internet format,
	Xand since many USENET sites do not yet have mailers
	Xcapable of understanding internet format,
	Xit would break the reply capability to completely sever the connection
	Xbetween the
	X.hf Path
	Xheader and the reply function.
	XIt is recognized that the path is not always a valid reply string
	Xin older implementations,
	Xand no requirement to fix this problem is placed on implementations.
	XHowever,
	Xthe existing convention of placing the site name and an
	X.cf !
	Xat the front of the path,
	Xand of starting the path with the site name,
	Xan
	X.cf ! ,
	Xand the user name,
	Xshould be maintained when possible.
	X.hn 2
	XOptional Headers
	X.hn 3
	XReply-To
	X.pg
	XThis line has the same format as
	X.hf From .
	XIf present,
	Xmailed replies to the author should be sent to the name given here.
	XOtherwise,
	Xreplies are mailed to the name on the
	X.hf From
	Xline.
	X(This does not prevent additional copies from being sent to recipients
	Xnamed by the replier,
	Xor on
	X.hf To
	Xor
	X.hf Cc
	Xlines.)
	XThe full name may be optionally given,
	Xin parentheses,
	Xas in the
	X.hf From
	Xline.
	X.hn 3
	XSender
	X.pg
	XThis field is present only if the submitter manually enters a
	X.hf From
	Xline.
	XIt is intended to record the entity responsible
	Xfor submitting the article to the network,
	Xand should be verified by the software at the submitting site.
	X.pg
	XFor example,
	Xif John Smith is visiting CCA and wishes to post an article to the network,
	Xusing friend Sarah Jones account,
	Xthe message might read
	X.sd
	XFrom: smith@ucbvax.uucp (John Smith)
	XSender: jones@cca.arpa (Sarah Jones)
	X.ed
	XIf a gateway program enters a mail message into the network at site
	X.cn sri-unix ,
	Xthe lines might read
	X.sd
	XFrom: John.Doe@A.CS.CMU.EDU
	XSender: network@sri-unix.ARPA
	X.ed
	XThe primary purpose of this field is to be able to track down articles
	Xto determine how they were entered into the network.
	XThe full name may be optionally given,
	Xin parentheses,
	Xas in the
	X.hf From
	Xline.
	X.hn 3
	XFollowup-To
	X.pg
	XThis line has the same format as
	X.hf Newsgroups .
	XIf present,
	Xfollow-up articles are to be posted
	Xto the newsgroup or newsgroups listed here.
	XIf this line is not present,
	Xfollowups are posted to the newsgroup or newsgroups listed in the
	X.hf Newsgroups
	Xline.
	X.pg
	XIf the keyword
	X.i poster
	Xis present, followup articles are not permitted. The message should
	Xbe mailed to the submitter of the article via mail.
	X.hn 3
	XExpires
	X.pg
	XThis line,
	Xif present,
	Xis in a legal USENET date format.
	XIt specifies a suggested expiration date for the article.
	XIf not present,
	Xthe local default expiration date is used.
	X.P
	XThis field is intended to be used to clean up
	Xarticles with a limited usefulness,
	Xor to keep important articles around for longer than usual.
	XFor example,
	Xa message announcing an upcoming seminar
	Xcould have an expiration date the day after the seminar,
	Xsince the message is not useful after the seminar is over.
	XSince local sites have local policies for expiration of news
	X(depending on available disk space,
	Xfor instance),
	Xusers are discouraged from providing expiration dates for articles
	Xunless there is a natural expiration date associated with the topic.
	XSystem software should almost never provide a default
	X.hf Expires
	Xline.
	XLeave it out and allow local policies to be used
	Xunless there is a good reason not to.
	X.hn 3
	XReferences
	X.pg
	XThis field lists the Message-ID's of any articles prompting
	Xthe submission of this article.
	XIt is required for all follow-up articles,
	Xand forbidden when a new subject is raised.
	XImplementations should provide a follow-up command,
	Xwhich allows a user to post a follow-up article.
	XThis command should generate a
	X.hf Subject
	Xline which is the same as the original article,
	Xexcept that if the original subject does not begin
	Xwith \*(lqRe: \*(rq or \*(lqre: \*(rq,
	Xthe four characters \*(lqRe: \*(rq are inserted before the subject.
	XIf there is no
	X.hf References
	Xline on the original header,
	Xthe
	X.hf References
	Xline should contain the Message-ID of the original article
	X(including the angle brackets).
	XIf the original article does have a
	X.hf References
	Xline,
	Xthe followup article should have a
	X.hf References
	Xline containing the text of the original
	X.hf References
	Xline,
	Xa blank,
	Xand the Message-ID of the original article.
	X.pg
	XThe purpose of the
	X.hf References
	Xheader is to allow articles to be grouped into conversations
	Xby the user interface program.
	XThis allows conversations within a newsgroup to be kept together,
	Xand potentially users might shut off entire conversations
	Xwithout unsubscribing to a newsgroup.
	XUser interfaces need not make use of this header,
	Xbut all automatically generated followups should generate the
	X.hf References
	Xline for the benefit of systems that do use it,
	Xand manually generated followups
	X.i e\f1.\fPg ., (
	Xtyped in well after the original article has been printed by the machine)
	Xshould be encouraged to include them as well.
	X.pg
	XIt is permissible to not include the entire previous 
	X.hf References
	Xline if it is too long. An attempt should be made to include a reasonable
	Xnumber of backwards references.
	X.hn 3
	XControl
	X.pg
	XIf an article contains a
	X.hf Control
	Xline,
	Xthe article is a control message.
	XControl messages are used for communication among USENET host machines,
	Xnot to be read by users.
	XControl messages are distributed by the same newsgroup mechanism
	Xas ordinary messages.
	XThe body of the
	X.hf Control
	Xheader line is the message to the host.
	X.pg
	XFor upward compatibility,
	Xmessages that match the newsgroup pattern
	X.ng all.all.ctl
	Xshould also be interpreted as control messages.
	XIf no
	X.hf Control
	Xheader is present on such messages,
	Xthe subject is used as the control message.
	XHowever,
	Xmessages on newsgroups matching this pattern do not conform to this standard.
	X.pg
	XAlso for upward compatibility,
	Xif the first 5 characters of the 
	X.hf Subject:
	Xline are \*(lqcmsg\*(rq, the rest of the
	X.hf Subject:
	Xline should be interpreted as a control message.
	X.hn 3
	XDistribution
	X.pg
	XThis line is used to alter the distribution scope of the message.
	XIt has the same format as the
	X.hf Newsgroups
	Xline.
	XUser subscriptions are still controlled by
	X.hf Newsgroups ,
	Xbut the message is sent to all systems subscribing to the newsgroups
	Xon the
	X.hf Distribution
	Xline instead of the
	X.hf Newsgroups
	Xline.
	XThus, 
	Xa car for sale in New Jersey might have headers including
	X.sd
	XNewsgroups: rec.auto,misc.forsale
	XDistribution: nj
	X.ed
	Xso that it would only go to persons subscribing to
	X.ng rec.auto
	Xor
	X.ng misc.forsale
	Xwithin New Jersey.
	XThe intent of this header is to restrict
	Xthe distribution of a newsgroup further,
	Xnot to increase it.
	XA local newsgroup,
	Xsuch as
	X.ng nj.crazy-eddie ,
	Xwill probably not be propagated by sites outside New Jersey
	Xthat do not show such a newsgroup as valid.
	XFollowup articles should default to the same
	X.hf Distribution
	Xline as the original article,
	Xbut the user can change it to a more limited one,
	Xor escalate the distribution
	Xif it was originally restricted
	Xand a more widely distributed reply is appropriate.
	X.hn 3
	XOrganization
	X.pg
	XThe text of this line is a short phrase describing the organization
	Xto which the sender belongs,
	Xor to which the machine belongs.
	XThe intent of this line is to help identify the person posting the message,
	Xsince site names are often cryptic enough to make it hard
	Xto recognize the organization by the electronic address.
	X.hn 3
	XKeywords
	X.pg
	XA few, well selected keywords identifying this article should be on
	Xthis line. This is used as an aid in determining if this article is
	Xinteresting to the reader.
	X.hn 3
	XSummary
	X.pg
	XThis line (lines) should contain a brief summary of the article. It is
	Xusually used as part of a followup to another article. Again, it is
	Xvery useful to the reader in determining whether to read the article.
	X.hn 3
	XApproved
	X.pg
	XThis line is required for any message posted to a moderated newsgroup.
	XIt should be added by the moderator and consist of his mail address.
	X.hn 3
	XLines
	X.pg
	XThis contains a count of the number of lines in the article.
	X.hn 3
	XXref
	X.pg
	XThis line contains the name of the site (with domains omitted) and a
	Xwhite space separated list of colon separated pairs of newsgroup names
	Xand article numbers, these are the newsgroups listed in the
	X.hf Newsgroups
	Xline and the corresponding article numbers from the spool directory.
	X.hn 3
	XNF-ID
	X.pg
	XThis line is inserted by the 
	X.i notesfile
	Xsystem and is not of any use to programs following this standard.
	X.hn 3
	XNF-From
	X.pg
	XThis is another 
	X.i notesfile
	Xinserted header that is ignored by everything except notesfiles.
	X.hn 1
	XControl Messages
	X.pg
	XThis section lists the control messages currently defined.
	XThe body of the
	X.hf Control
	Xheader is the control message.
	XMessages are a sequence of zero or more words,
	Xseparated by white space (blanks or tabs).
	XThe first word is the name of the control message,
	Xremaining words are parameters to the message.
	XThe remainder of the header and the body of the message
	Xare also potential parameters;
	Xfor example,
	Xthe
	X.hf From
	Xline might suggest an address to which a response is to be mailed.
	X.pg
	XImplementors and administrators may choose to allow control messages
	Xto be carried out automatically,
	Xor to queue them for manual processing.
	XHowever,
	Xmanually processed messages should be dealt with promptly.
	X.pg
	XFailed control messages should NOT be mailed to the originator of the message,
	Xbut to the local \*(lqusenet\*(rq account.
	X.hn 2
	XCancel
	X.pg l
	X.sd
	Xcancel <Message-ID>
	X.ed
	XIf an article with the given Message-ID is present on the local system,
	Xthe article is cancelled.
	XThis mechanism allows a user to cancel an article
	Xafter the article has been distributed over the network.
	X.pg
	XIf the system is unable to cancel the article as requested, it should not
	Xforward the cancellation request to its neighbor systems.
	X.pg
	XOnly the author of the article or the local super user
	Xis allowed to use this message.
	XThe verified sender of a message is the
	X.hf Sender
	Xline,
	Xor if no
	X.hf Sender
	Xline is present,
	Xthe
	X.hf From
	Xline.
	XThe verified sender of the cancel message must be the same
	Xas either the
	X.hf Sender
	Xor
	X.hf From
	Xfield of the original message.
	XA verified sender in the cancel message is allowed to match an unverified
	X.hf From
	Xin the original message.
	X.hn 2
	XIhave/Sendme
	X.pg l
	X.sd
	Xihave <Message-ID list> <remotesys>
	Xsendme <Message-ID list> <remotesys>
	X.ed
	XThis message is part of the
	X.pa ihave/sendme
	Xprotocol,
	Xwhich allows one site
	X(say
	X.cn A )
	Xto tell another site
	X.cn B ) (
	Xthat a particular message has been received on
	X.cn A .
	XSuppose that site
	X.cn A
	Xreceives article
	X.cf <1234@ucbvax.Berkeley.edu> ,
	Xand wishes to transmit the article to site
	X.cn B .
	X.cn A
	Xsends the control message
	X.cf "ihave <1234@ucbvax.Berkeley.edu> A"
	Xto site
	X.cn B
	X(by posting it to newsgroup
	X.bi B ). \f3to.\fP
	X.cn B
	Xresponds with the control message
	X.cf "sendme <1234@ucbvax.Berkeley.edu> B"
	X(on newsgroup
	X.bi A ) \f3to.\fP
	Xif it has not already received the article.
	XUpon receiving the
	X.pa sendme
	Xmessage,
	X.cn A
	Xsends the article to
	X.cn B .
	X.pg
	XThis protocol can be used to cut down on redundant traffic between sites.
	XIt is optional and should be used
	Xonly if the particular situation makes it worthwhile.
	XFrequently,
	Xthe outcome is that,
	Xsince most original messages are short,
	Xand since there is a high overhead to start sending a new message with UUCP,
	Xit costs as much to send the
	X.pa ihave
	Xas it would cost to send the article itself.
	X.pg
	XOne possible solution to this overhead problem is to batch requests.
	XSeveral Message-ID's may be announced or requested in one message.
	XIf no Message-ID's are listed in the control message,
	Xthe body of the message should be scanned for Message-ID's,
	Xone per line.
	X.hn 2
	XNewgroup
	X.sd
	Xnewgroup <groupname> [moderated]
	X.ed
	X.pg
	XThis control message creates a new newsgroup with the name given.
	XSince no articles may be posted or forwarded until a newsgroup is created,
	Xthis message is required before a newsgroup can be used.
	XThe body of the message is expected to be a short paragraph
	Xdescribing the intended use of the newsgroup.
	X.pg
	XIf the second argument is present and is the keyword
	X.i moderated ,
	Xthe group should be created moderated instead of the default unmoderated.
	XThe newgroup message should be ignored unless there is an
	X.hf Approved
	Xline in the same message header.
	X.hn 2
	XRmgroup
	X.sd
	Xrmgroup <groupname>
	X.ed
	X.pg
	XThis message removes a newsgroup with the given name.
	XSince the newsgroup is removed from every site on the network,
	Xthis command should be used carefully by a responsible administrator.
	XThe rmgroup message should be ignored unless there is an
	X.hf Approved:
	Xline in the same message header.
	X.hn 2
	XSendsys
	X.sd
	Xsendsys	(no arguments)
	X.ed
	X.pg
	XThe
	X.i sys
	Xfile,
	Xlisting all neighbors and which newsgroups are sent to each neighbor,
	Xwill be mailed to the author of the control message
	X.hf Reply-to , (
	Xif present,
	Xotherwise
	X.hf From ).
	XThis information is considered public information,
	Xand it is a requirement of membership in USENET
	Xthat this information be provided on request,
	Xeither automatically in response to this control message,
	Xor manually,
	Xby mailing the requested information to the author of the message.
	XThis information is used to keep the map of USENET up to date,
	Xand to determine where netnews is sent.
	X.pg
	XThe format of the file mailed back to the author
	Xshould be the same as that of the
	X.i sys
	Xfile.
	XThis format has one line per neighboring site
	X(plus one line for the local site),
	Xcontaining four colon separated fields.
	XThe first field has the site name of the neighbor,
	Xthe second field has a newsgroup pattern
	Xdescribing the newsgroups sent to the neighbor.
	XThe third and fourth fields are not defined by this standard.
	XA sample response is:
	X.sd
	XFrom cbosgd!mark  Sun Mar 27 20:39:37 1983
	XSubject: response to your sendsys request
	XTo: mark@cbosgd.UUCP
	X
	XResponding-System: cbosgd.UUCP
	Xcbosgd:osg,cb,btl,bell,world,comp,sci,rec,talk,misc,news,soc,to,test
	Xucbvax:world,comp,to.ucbvax:L:
	Xcbosg:world,comp,bell,btl,cb,osg,to.cbosg:F:/usr/spool/outnews/cbosg
	Xcbosgb:osg,to.cbosgb:F:/usr/spool/outnews/cbosgb
	Xsescent:world,comp,bell,btl,cb,to.sescent:F:/usr/spool/outnews/sescent
	Xnpois:world,comp,bell,btl,ug,to.npois:F:/usr/spool/outnews/npois
	Xmhuxi:world,comp,bell,btl,ug,to.mhuxi:F:/usr/spool/outnews/mhuxi
	X.ed
	X.hn 2
	XSenduuname
	X.pg l
	X.sd
	Xsenduuname	(no arguments)
	X.ed
	XThe
	X.i uuname (1)
	Xprogram is run,
	Xand the output is mailed to the author of the control message
	X.hf Reply-to , (
	Xif present,
	Xotherwise
	X.hf From ).
	XThis program lists all UUCP neighbors of the local site.
	XThis information is used to make maps of the UUCP network.
	XThe
	X.i sys
	Xfile is
	X.b not
	Xthe same as the UUCP
	X.i L.sys
	Xfile.
	XThe
	X.i L.sys
	Xfile should
	X.b never
	Xbe transmitted to another party
	Xwithout the consent of the sites whose passwords are listed therein.
	X.pg
	XIt is optional for a site to provide this information.
	XSome reply should be made to the author of the control message,
	Xso that a transmission error won't be blamed.
	XIt is also permissible for a site to run the
	X.i uuname
	Xprogram
	X(or in some other way determine the UUCP neighbors)
	Xand edit the output,
	Xeither automatically or manually,
	Xbefore mailing the reply back to the author.
	XThe file should contain one site per line,
	Xbeginning with the UUCP site name.
	XAdditional information may be included,
	Xseparated from the site name by a blank or tab.
	XThe phone number or password for the site should
	X.ng not
	Xbe included,
	Xas the reply is considered to be in the public domain.
	X(The
	X.i uuname
	Xprogram will send only the site name and not the entire contents of the
	X.i L.sys
	Xfile,
	Xthus,
	Xphone numbers and passwords are not transmitted.)
	X.pg
	XThe purpose of this message was to generate and maintain UUCP mail routing maps.
	XThus, connections over which mail can be sent using the
	X.cf site!user
