	X.hf From ).
	X.hn 2
	Xcheckgroups
	X.pg
	XThe message body is a list of \*(lqofficial\*(rq newsgroups and their
	Xdescription, one group per line.  They are compared against the  list
	Xof active newsgroups on the current site. The names of any obsolete or new 
	Xnewsgroups are mailed to the used \*(lqusenet\*(rq and descriptions  of the
	Xnew newsgroups are added to the help file used when posting news.
	X.hn 1
	XTransmission Methods
	X.pg
	XUSENET is not a physical network,
	Xbut rather a logical network
	Xresting on top of several existing physical networks.
	XThese networks include,
	Xbut are not limited to,
	XUUCP,
	Xthe ARPANET,
	Xan Ethernet,
	Xthe BLICN network,
	Xan NSC Hyperchannel,
	Xand a BERKNET.
	XWhat is important is that two neighboring systems on USENET
	Xhave some method to get a new article,
	Xin the format listed here,
	Xfrom one system to the other,
	Xand once on the receiving system,
	Xprocessed by the netnews software on that system.
	X(On
	X.ux
	Xsystems,
	Xthis usually means the
	X.i rnews
	Xprogram being run with the article on the standard input.)
	X.pg
	XIt is not a requirement that USENET sites have mail systems
	Xcapable of understanding the ARPA Internet mail syntax,
	Xbut it is strongly recommended.
	XSince
	X.hf From ,
	X.hf Reply-To ,
	Xand
	X.hf Sender
	Xlines use the Internet syntax, 
	Xreplies will be difficult or impossible without an internet mailer.
	XA site without an internet mailer can attempt to use the
	X.hf Path
	Xheader line for replies,
	Xbut this field is not guaranteed to be a working path for replies.
	XIn any event,
	Xany site generating or forwarding news messages
	Xmust have an internet address that allows them
	Xto receive mail from sites with internet mailers,
	Xand they must include their internet address on their From line.
	X.hn 2
	XRemote Execution
	X.pg
	XSome networks permit direct remote command execution.
	XOn these networks,
	Xnews may be forwarded by spooling the
	X.i rnews
	Xcommand with the article on the standard input.
	XFor example,
	Xif the remote system is called
	X.cn remote ,
	Xnews would be sent over a UUCP link with the command
	X.sd c
	Xuux \- remote!rnews
	X.ed
	Xand on a Berknet,
	X.sd c
	Xnet \-mremote rnews
	X.ed
	XIt is important that the article be sent via a reliable mechanism,
	Xnormally involving the possibility of spooling,
	Xrather than direct real-time remote execution.
	XThis is because,
	Xif the remote system is down,
	Xa direct execution command will fail,
	Xand the article will never be delivered.
	XIf the article is spooled,
	Xit will eventually be delivered when both systems are up.
	X.hn 2
	XTransfer by Mail
	X.pg
	XOn some systems,
	Xdirect remote spooled execution is not possible.
	XHowever,
	Xmost systems support electronic mail,
	Xand a news article can be sent as mail.
	XOne approach is to send a mail message
	Xwhich is identical to the news message:
	Xthe mail headers are the news headers,
	Xand the mail body is the news body.
	XBy convention,
	Xthis mail is sent to the user
	X.i newsmail
	Xon the remote machine.
	X.pg
	XOne problem with this method is that it may not be possible to convince
	Xthe mail system that the
	X.hf From
	Xline of the message is valid,
	Xsince the mail message was generated by a program
	Xon a system different from the source of the news article.
	XAnother problem is that error messages caused by the mail transmission
	Xwould be sent to the originator of the news article,
	Xwho has no control over news transmission between two cooperating hosts
	Xand does not know who to contact.
	XTransmission error messages should be directed to a responsible
	Xcontact person on the sending machine.
	X.pg
	XA solution to this problem is to encapsulate the news article
	Xinto a mail message,
	Xsuch that the entire article
	X(headers and body)
	Xare part of the body of the mail message.
	XThe convention here is that such mail is sent to user
	X.i rnews
	Xon the remote system.
	XA mail message body is generated by prepending the letter
	X.qp N
	Xto each line of the news article,
	Xand then attaching whatever mail headers are convenient to generate.
	XThe
	X.qp N 's
	Xare attached to prevent any special lines in the news article
	Xfrom interfering with mail transmission,
	Xand to prevent any extra lines inserted by the mailer
	X(headers,
	Xblank lines,
	Xetc.)
	Xfrom becoming part of the news article.
	XA program on the receiving machine receives mail to
	X.i rnews ,
	Xextracting the article itself and invoking the
	X.i rnews
	Xprogram.
	XAn example in this format might look like this:
	X.sd
	XDate: Monday, 3 Jan 83 08:33:47 MST
	XFrom: news@cbosgd.UUCP
	XSubject: network news article
	XTo: rnews@npois.UUCP
	X
	XNPath: cbosgd!mhuxj!harpo!utah-cs!sask!derek
	XNFrom: derek@sask.UUCP (Derek Andrew)
	XNNewsgroups: net.test
	XNSubject: necessary test
	XNMessage-ID: <176@sask.UUCP>
	XNDate: Monday, 3 Jan 83 00:59:15 MST
	XN
	XNThis really is a test.  If anyone out there more than 6 
	XNhops away would kindly confirm this note I would
	XNappreciate it.  We suspect that our news postings
	XNare not getting out into the world.
	XN
	X.ed
	X.pg
	XUsing mail solves the spooling problem,
	Xsince mail must always be spooled if the destination host is down.
	XHowever,
	Xit adds more overhead to the transmission process
	X(to encapsulate and extract the article)
	Xand makes it harder for software to give different priorities
	Xto news and mail.
	X.hn 2
	XBatching
	X.pg
	XSince news articles are usually short,
	Xand since a large number of messages
	Xare often sent between two sites in a day,
	Xit may make sense to batch news articles.
	XSeveral articles can be combined into one large article,
	Xusing conventions agreed upon in advance by the two sites.
	XOne such batching scheme is described here;
	Xits use is highly recommended.
	X.pg
	XNews articles are combined into a script, separated by a header of the form:
	X.sd
	X#! rnews 1234
	X.ed
	Xwhere
	X.i 1234
	Xis the length,
	Xin bytes,
	Xof the article.
	XEach such line is followed by an article containing the given number of bytes.
	X(The newline at the end of each line of the article is counted as one byte,
	Xfor purposes of this count, even if it is stored as
	X.qc "CARRIAGE RETURN\s+2><\s-2LINE FEED" \&.)
	XFor example,
	Xa batch of articles might look like this:
	X.sd
	X#! rnews 207
	XFrom: jerry@eagle.uucp (Jerry Schwarz)
	XPath: cbosgd!mhuxj!mhuxt!eagle!jerry
	XNewsgroups: net.general
	XSubject: Usenet Etiquette -- Please Read
	XMessage-ID: <642@eagle.UUCP>
	XDate: Friday, 19 Nov 82 16:14:55 EST
	X
	XHere is an important message about USENET Etiquette.
	X#! rnews 203
	XFrom: jerry@eagle.uucp (Jerry Schwarz)
	XPath: cbosgd!mhuxj!mhuxt!eagle!jerry
	XNewsgroups: net.followup
	XSubject: Notes on Etiquette article
	XMessage-ID: <643@eagle.UUCP>
	XDate: Friday, 19 Nov 82 17:24:12 EST
	X
	XThere was something I forgot to mention in the last message.
	X.ed
	XBatched news is recognized because the first character in the message is
	X.qp # .
	XThe message is then passed to the unbatcher for interpretation.
	X.pg
	XThe second argument (in this example
	X.i rnews ),
	Xdetermines which batching scheme is being used. Cooperating sites
	Xmay use whatever scheme is appropriate for them.
	X.hn 1
	XThe News Propagation Algorithm
	X.pg
	XThis section describes the overall scheme of USENET and the algorithm
	Xfollowed by sites in propagating news to the entire network.
	XSince all sites are affected by incorrectly formatted articles
	Xand by propagation errors,
	Xit is important for the method to be standardized.
	X.pg
	XUSENET is a directed graph.
	XEach node in the graph is a host computer,
	Xand each arc in the graph is a transmission path
	Xfrom one host to another host.
	XEach arc is labeled with a newsgroup pattern,
	Xspecifying which newsgroup classes are forwarded along that link.
	XMost arcs are bidirectional,
	Xthat is,
	Xif site
	X.cn A
	Xsends a class of newsgroups to site
	X.cn B ,
	Xthen site
	X.cn B
	Xusually sends the same class of newsgroups to site
	X.cn A .
	XThis bidirectionality is not,
	Xhowever,
	Xrequired.
	X.pg
	XUSENET is made up of many subnetworks.
	XEach subnet has a name,
	Xsuch as
	X.ng comp
	Xor
	X.ng btl .
	XEach subnet is a connected graph,
	Xthat is,
	Xa path exists from every node to every other node in the subnet.
	XIn addition,
	Xthe entire graph is
	X(theoretically)
	Xconnected.
	X(In practice,
	Xsome political considerations have caused some sites
	Xto be unable to post articles reaching the rest of the network.)
	X.pg
	XAn article is posted on one machine to a list of newsgroups.
	XThat machine accepts it locally,
	Xthen forwards it to all its neighbors that are interested
	Xin at least one of the newsgroups of the message.
	X(Site
	X.cn A
	Xdeems site
	X.cn B
	Xto be \*(lqinterested\*(rq in a newsgroup
	Xif the newsgroup matches the pattern on the arc from
	X.cn A
	Xto
	X.cn B .
	XThis pattern is stored in a file on the
	X.cn A
	Xmachine.)
	XThe sites receiving the incoming article examine it
	Xto make sure they really want the article,
	Xaccept it locally,
	Xand then in turn forward the article to all
	X.i their
	Xinterested neighbors.
	XThis process continues until the entire network has seen the article.
	X.pg
	XAn important part of the algorithm is the prevention of loops.
	XThe above process would cause a message to loop along a cycle forever.
	XIn particular,
	Xwhen site
	X.cn A
	Xsends an article to site
	X.cn B ,
	Xsite
	X.cn B
	Xwill send it back to site
	X.cn A ,
	Xwhich will send it to site
	X.cn B ,
	Xand so on.
	XOne solution to this is the history mechanism.
	XEach site keeps track of all articles it has seen
	X(by their Message-ID)
	Xand whenever an article comes in that it has already seen,
	Xthe incoming article is discarded immediately.
	XThis solution is sufficient to prevent loops,
	Xbut additional optimizations can be made to avoid sending articles to sites
	Xthat will simply throw them away.
	X.pg
	XOne optimization is that an article should never be sent to a machine
	Xlisted in the
	X.hf Path
	Xline of the header.
	XWhen a machine name is in the
	X.hf Path
	Xline,
	Xthe message is known to have passed through the machine.
	XAnother optimization is that,
	Xif the article originated on site
	X.cn A ,
	Xthen site
	X.cn A
	Xhas already seen the article.
	X.P
	XThus,
	Xif an article is posted to newsgroup
	X.ng misc.misc ,
	Xit will match the pattern
	X.ng misc.all
	X(where
	X.ng all
	Xis a metasymbol that matches any string),
	Xand will be forwarded to all sites that subscribe to
	X.ng misc.all
	X(as determined by what their neighbors send them).
	XThese sites make up the
	X.ng misc
	Xsubnetwork.
	XAn article posted to
	X.ng btl.general
	Xwill reach all sites receiving
	X.ng btl.all ,
	Xbut will not reach sites that do not get
	X.ng btl.all .
	XIn effect,
	Xthe articles reaches the
	X.ng btl
	Xsubnetwork.
	XAn article posted to newsgroups
	X.ng misc.misc,btl.general
	Xwill reach all sites subscribing to either of the two classes.
